Yeah, considering the kinds of things apps tend to do with inbound email, I don't really want to have a setting that disables webhook validation. It'd be too easy for people to unintentionally introduce really serious vulnerabilities in their apps.

It sounds like you have a very specific use case in mind. (Iterating through enough payloads that the validation overhead is an issue, in a debug environment, but not in the context of tests. Fuzzing?)

If monkey-patching feels wrong, another (fully supported, non-brittle) approach is to subclass Anymail's webhook views and override anything you want. You could add your own setting to skip security checks:

```python
from anymail.webhooks.mailgun import MailgunInboundWebhookView

class SecurityOptionalInboundView(MailgunInboundWebhookView):
    def run_validators(self):
        if settings.DANGEROUSLY_SKIP_WEBHOOK_VALIDATION:
            pass  # (or maybe throw an error in production)
        else:
            super(SecurityOptionalInboundView, self).run_validators()
```

Then in your urls.py, hook up your customized view rather than including Anymail's urls.

For ``char``, your code should work now as a side effect of the latest commit. Note that certain special tuple-style types cannot be passed by reference or pointer, e.g.
```
void foo(std::tuple<T1, T2, ..>&);
void foo(std::pair<T1, T2>*);
```
